n":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Strivelyn was born in 1262, in Cadder, Lanarkshire, Scotland, his father, John de Strivelyn of Ochiltree, was 22 and his mother, Lady of Scotland, was 9. He had at least 1 son with Marie MacDúbhgaill - Heiress of Rathoran. He died in 1295, in Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1262–1295":"1262–1295","1272–1295":"1272–1295","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","1288–1323":"1288–1323","1283–1339":"1283–1339","1294–1339":"1294–1339","1240–1270":"1240–1270","1253–Female":"1253–Surnud","1323":"1323","1267":"1267","1288":"1288","1253":"125